17.sridhara:
The threefold division of charity, as promised earlier, is now stated: “dātavyam iti” — with the conviction that “this must be given,” the gift that is given; “anupakāriṇe” — to one who is unable to return the favor.

“In deśa (place), kāla (time), and pātra (recipient)” — the instrumental case here is to be taken as associative (sāhacarya), i.e., “in association with proper place, time, and recipient.”
“Deśa” — such as Kurukṣetra and so on;
“Kāla” — such as the time of eclipses and the like;
“Pātra” — one who is a qualified recipient, such as a Brahmin endowed with austerity and scriptural learning (tapas, śruti, etc.).

Or, alternatively, “pātre” may be taken as a noun in the fourth case (dative), and the form is a tṛjanta (verbal derivative noun), meaning “protector.” That is, he who protects the donor from all kinds of calamities — such a one is indeed the recipient. The gift that is of this kind is called sāttvika.
